{
  "texts": [
    "The isomorphism Φ is compatible with the quasi-Hamiltonian structures on E Θ and E Θ.",
    "This conjecture is quite natural: Indeed, it is known that the Fourier transform induces a symplectic isomorphism of wild character varieties in the case of connections on P 1 with an unramified irregular singularity at infinity of order 2 together with regular singularities at finite distance [Boa15a].",
    "Furthermore, in [Sza15] it is shown that in this case the Fourier transform preserves the full hyperkähler structure of the moduli space.",
    "Remark 5.9.",
    "We also expect that, in the case where there is only one active exponent of the form ⟨z s/r ⟩ with s > r and r, s coprime, by considering the recessive or subdominant solutions as in [Boa15b], the wild character variety is isomorphic to a moduli space of configuration of points in a projective space, and that the Fourier transform of Stokes data is related to the Gale transform of point configurations."
  ]
}